# FlowForge — Cursor Rules

## Stack
- Backend: Node.js, Express.js, TypeScript
- Frontend: React 18, TypeScript, ReactFlow, TailwindCSS
- DBs: PostgreSQL via Supabase (users, tenants, workflows, executions, integrations),
       MongoDB Atlas (workflow DAG definitions, execution logs)
- Auth: JWT (access token 15min, refresh token 7d)
- LLM: Groq API (Llama 3.3 70B) with structured JSON output (Zod schema validation)
- Deployment: Vercel (frontend), Render (backend), Supabase, MongoDB Atlas

## Development Rules
1. Before writing ANY code, propose a step-by-step plan and wait for approval
2. Use TypeScript strictly — never use `any`, always infer from Zod schemas
3. All API routes follow /api/v1/ prefix for versioning
4. Every database operation uses parameterized queries — no string concatenation
5. All inputs validated with Zod before processing
6. Error responses always follow { success: false, error: string, code: string }
7. Success responses always follow { success: true, data: T }
8. Never start a dev server or curl localhost in responses
9. Run `tsc --noEmit` after every change
10. MongoDB for: workflow DAG JSON, execution step logs
    PostgreSQL for: users, tenants, workflows, workflow_executions, tenant_integrations

## What NOT to do
- Do not add features outside SPEC.md scope
- Do not use `any` TypeScript type
- Do not use ORM magic — write explicit queries
- Do not create new npm packages without asking
- Do not use classes — functional patterns only
